1 Introduction In physics textbooks, we often come across the terms &ldquo;pseudo-vector&rdquo; and &ldquo;pseudo-scalar.&rdquo;
In fact, on a 3-dimensional manifold, a &ldquo;pseudo-vector&rdquo; is the exterior product of two tangent vectors, denoted as $v\in T_pM\wedge T_pM=\bigwedge^2(T_pM)$, while a &ldquo;pseudo-scalar&rdquo; is the exterior product of three tangent vectors, denoted as $s\in T_pM\wedge T_pM\wedge T_pM=\bigwedge^3(T_pM)$.
When equipped with an inner product (or non-degenerate bilinear form), there exists a Hodge duality between $\bigwedge^2(T_pM)$ and $\bigwedge^1(T_pM)$, which leads us to mistakenly consider the pseudo-vector as a vector.
